{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"40d8f8a9-05a8-4161-8c2a-4b44ca15c53e","content":"Here's how to set up **NuGet trusted publishing** using GitHub Actions OIDC — no API keys needed.\n\n## 1. Configure nuget.org\n\n1. Sign in to [nuget.org](https://www.nuget.org) → **Account Settings** → **Trusted Publishers**\n2. Add a trusted publisher:\n   - **Repository owner**: `myorg`\n   - **Repository name**: `mylib`\n   - **Workflow filename**: `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment** *(recommended)*: `nuget` (adds an approval gate)\n\n## 2. Create GitHub Environment (optional but recommended)\n\nIn your repo → **Settings → Environments** → create `nuget` with protection rules (e.g. required reviewers, restrict to `main` branch / version tags).\n\n## 3. Add the workflow\n\nCreate `.github/workflows/publish.yml`:\n\n```yaml\nname: Publish to NuGet\n\non:\n  push:\n    tags: ['v*']\n\njobs:\n  publish:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    environment: nuget            # must match nuget.org config\n    permissions:\n      id-token: write             # OIDC token for trusted publishing\n      contents: read\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - uses: actions/setup-dotnet@v4\n        with:\n          dotnet-version: '8.0.x'\n\n      - run: dotnet pack src/MyLib/MyLib.csproj -c Release -o ./nupkg\n\n      - name: Push to NuGet\n        run: >\n          dotnet nuget push ./nupkg/*.nupkg\n          --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n## How it works\n\n- `id-token: write` lets the runner mint a short-lived OIDC JWT.\n- nuget.org verifies the token's claims (repo, workflow, environment) against your trusted-publisher config.\n- No secrets stored anywhere — the trust is based on the GitHub ↔ NuGet OIDC federation.\n\n## To publish\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe workflow triggers, packs the project, and pushes the `.nupkg` using the OIDC identity. If you configured the `nuget` environment with reviewers, the push will wait for approval.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2b128554-9e97-4bb7-b227-83a63964ed4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to set up secure NuGet publishing from GitHub Actions using trusted publishing (without API keys). This is a knowledge/guidance question, not a code task. Let me provide a concise answer.\n\nThe modern approach is to use NuGet's trusted publishing with OIDC tokens, which was introduced in 2023-2024. This allows GitHub Actions to authenticate to nuget.org without storing API keys as secrets.\n\nLet me outline the steps:\n\n1. **On nuget.org**: Link the GitHub repository as a trusted publisher for the package.\n2. **In GitHub Actions**: Use a workflow that requests an OIDC token and uses `dotnet nuget push` with the `--api-key` set to the OIDC token.\n\n\n3. The workflow needs `permissions: id-token: write` to request the OIDC token from GitHub.\n\nI should double-check the exact configuration details on nuget.org's side, as the trusted publisher setup might have specific requirements around which workflows or branches can publish. I'm going to walk through a concrete workflow example that handles the build, packing, and publishing steps with OIDC authentication to NuGet.org, then you'd configure the trusted publisher relationship on NuGet's side to complete the setup.","outputTokens":1453},"id":"daaeb865-ceb6-4281-b6e6-5cba238bcb9a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:41:45.869Z","parentId":"cd71ab37-35fe-47c4-ace6-7bf4025dc580"}
